message: Focus on cooking raw ingredients with the stove first. Cooked proteins and cooked vegetables usually yield value 20. Combining two cooked proteins (e.g., cooked egg + cooked bacon) gives value 40. Combining a cooked protein with a cooked vegetable (e.g., cooked egg + cooked pepper) gives value 60. The highest value combination is usually a cooked protein combo + cooked vegetable (e.g., cooked bacon and egg + cooked pepper) or a cooked protein + two cooked vegetables, reaching value 80. Crucially, DO NOT combine any valuable cooked item with a cooked grain (like bread, tortilla, rice, wheat) as this results in a value of 0. Also, the 'water' tool is detrimental and causes negative values. Submit once you reach a high value, preferably 80, and avoid combining with grains or using water.

message:
Hey future player! Here are some tips based on my experience:
1. The 游댠 stove is your best friend. Always use it on raw ingredients first (e.g., raw bacon, raw egg, vegetables) to make them 'cooked' and increase their base value to 20. BUT, using it twice on an already cooked item will make it 'overcooked' and tank its value!
2. 游눦 water is indeed useless, as the previous player warned.
3. Combine cooked items with different features. For example, 'cooked protein' + 'cooked vegetable' often leads to good value (e.g., 60). Adding a third cooked item (another protein or vegetable) can often bring it up to 80.
4. Be careful with grains (wheat, rice, bread, tortilla). Sometimes they can combine well (like cooked bacon + bread for a sandwich), but often, after cooking them with the stove, they remain at 0 value. Adding a 0-value item to an already high-value dish (like 80) can make the whole item drop to 0 or even negative value. It seems 'overcomplicating' a dish can penalize you.
5. Don't be greedy! If you reach a score of 80 and only have low-value ingredients or risky actions left, it's often safest to submit and secure that score. Good luck!

message: Always cook raw proteins and vegetables with the stove first; they become value 20. Combining one cooked protein and one cooked vegetable makes a value 60 item. Adding a *second* cooked protein or cooked vegetable to that 60-value item usually results in an 80-value item. Avoid adding cooked grains (wheat, corn, bread) to high-value dishes, as this can drop the value to 0. Water seems useless.

message: Focus on cooking all 'raw' ingredients with the 'stove' first, especially proteins and vegetables, as this increases their individual value (20). Grains often don't gain value alone but become 'cooked'. Combine a 'cooked protein' with a 'cooked vegetable' for 60 points. Then add a 'cooked grain' to this medley for 80 points. A combination of three *different* cooked categories (protein, vegetable, grain) seems to be the sweet spot for 80 points. Do NOT add a fourth ingredient to an 80-point medley; it will become 'overcomplicated' and drop to 0 value. The 'water' tool is detrimental, avoid it completely. Always submit when you hit 80 points with a three-ingredient medley.
